description:
World Renowned Fatherhood Expert Dr Anna Machin reveals the #1 lie about monogamy, how cheating hijacks human brains, and the evolutionary truth behind love, trust, and fatherhood!

Dr Anna Machin is an evolutionary anthropologist and relationship scientist known for her groundbreaking research on human connection, love, fatherhood, and attachment. She is also the author of Why We Love: The New Science Behind Our Closest Relationships.


What you’ll learn:
◽️ How cheating hijacks the brain like an addictive drug
◽️ The evolutionary lie about monogamy & true love
◽️ Why modern fatherhood is more important than ever
◽️ The real reason we fall for the wrong person
◽️ How oxytocin, dopamine & DNA shape who we love and trust

—

comments.text: I absolutely loved this episode: As a man who has been married for over 30 years, has two adult children who I adore, and who (by all external measure) did fatherhood and the provider thing very well (built , grew and successfully sold a business)...I consider my marriage (and much of my personal life for that reason) a failure...despite my wife and I being looked upon as a success by most measures. I was taught that my role as a man and Father was to play a supporting role to my partner...doing this to the best of my ability resulted in the loss of emotional and physical intimacy with my wife (very early on)...and a lonely and insular life. Im trying to help my son avoid my mistakes...thatnk you for discussing this important topic.

comments.text: Hear me out. Steven seems like a good guy but he's either naive or he's playing a dodgy marketing game with these videos. His stats at the beginning re men and women looking for relationships (men more than women, apparently) contradict other 'studies' and 'surveys' I've seen. Plus, I'm sceptical of these studies generally as people give all sorts of answers they might not particularly agree with later-the idea of revealed and stated preferences, and Timur Kuran's idea of preference falsification, social pressure and expressed preferences. He is starting off with fairly dodgy facts and as a result coming to fairly dodgy conclusions. In other words, using emotional marketing to hook viewers in. This is isn't very honourable behaviour Steven, is it?

She made it clear that human brains are more complex than their natural drives—for example, how unkindness can override sexual attraction. Frankly, I find it strange how obsessed people in this comment section seem with this monogamy versus polyamory debate. comments.text:
This is a weird conversation. First, the presentation of monogamy vs polyamory isn't really presented honestly here. We are socially monogamous meaning we prefer pair bonds with allowance for separation and re-pairing, not one person ever always.

She calls out gibbons, and it's true - all animals that are "monogamous" in behavioral ecology have some prevalence of 'cheating' and 'divorce'. So in practice, the human inclination to pair up with one partner, and to cheat/separate actually is very in line with monogamous behavior in the animal kingdom.

It also puts the onus on natural vs practical, desirable, beneficial, etc. Monogamy is what humans usually end up going with for real benefits relating to social order, child survival and success, it has lower risks of failure.

Polyamory doesn't scale well, and it's easier to fail at. When done well, outcomes (around happiness and such) are similar to monogamy, but it's harder to achieve with polyamory. Polyamory also has other risks, such as increasing inequality because high performers can monopolize partners

comments.text:
I don’t agree with her take on polyamory at all. In my experience, it was the opposite of what she describes. I just got out of a polyamorous relationship where my partner was polyamorous and I was monogamous, and honestly, communication broke down constantly. When too many people are involved, things get messy, conversations slip through the cracks, and there just isn’t enough time to have them all.

What I noticed is that polyamory often looked less like “better communication” and more like avoiding real closeness with one person. And there’s always a hierarchy - ironically, the exact opposite of what polyamory is supposed to mean. At the end of the day, time and presence aren’t infinite, and those are exactly what a lasting relationship needs but what polyamory often can’t offer.

For me, it felt like spreading yourself thin instead of actually showing up fully - shielding yourself from getting too close, even though the definition of polyamory claims the opposite. I found a lot of contradictions in my relationship and in the polyamorous people I met. Never again - monogamy for the win!
comments.author: @mk7042
